\indent One unorthodox feature of $\mathrm{NFU}^{-\mathrm{AC}}$ is the fact that it proves that there are sets, for example $V$, which are not the same size as their own set of singletons. This motivates the introduction of the $T$ operation which is defined on cardinals, ordinals and equivalence classes of isomorphic well-founded relations, and the definition of Cantorian and strongly Cantorian sets. If $R$ is a relation then we use $[R]$ to denote the set of all relations isomorphic to $R$. If $F$ is a function and $X$ is a set then we write $F``X$ for the set of all things that can be obtained by applying $F$ to an element of $X$.

